<Layout title="Finger Placement and Posture | Harmonium Halt"
  description="Build the correct physical foundation. Proper technique prevents injury and builds long-term speed. Free harmonium lesson with interactive web harmonium tool.">
  <div class="bg-white border-b" style="border-color:rgba(28,16,8,.08)">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 py-2.5 breadcrumb">
      <a href="/">Home</a><span class="mx-1.5">›</span>
      <a href="/lessons">Lessons</a><span class="mx-1.5">›</span>
      <span>Finger Placement and Posture</span>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-8 sm:py-12">
    <div class="mb-6 sm:mb-8">
      <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-2 mb-4">
        <span class="badge badge-beginner capitalize">beginner</span>
        <span class="text-xs" style="color:rgba(28,16,8,.4);font-family:'Plus Jakarta Sans',sans-serif">⏱ 15 min · Lesson 4 of 8</span>
      </div>
      <h1 class="section-title text-2xl sm:text-3xl lg:text-4xl mb-3" style="color:#1c1008">Finger Placement and Posture</h1>
      <p class="text-sm sm:text-base leading-relaxed" style="color:rgba(28,16,8,.6);font-family:'Plus Jakarta Sans',sans-serif">Build the correct physical foundation. Proper technique prevents injury and builds long-term speed.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="rounded-xl p-4 sm:p-5 mb-6 border" style="background:#fef9f0;border-color:rgba(212,146,10,.25)">
      <h3 class="font-bold text-sm mb-3" style="color:#92400e;font-family:'Plus Jakarta Sans',sans-serif">📌 Key Takeaways</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-1.5">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-xs sm:text-sm" style="color:#92400e;font-family:'Plus Jakarta Sans',sans-serif"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" class="flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg>Use curved relaxed fingers — like holding a tennis ball</li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-xs sm:text-sm" style="color:#92400e;font-family:'Plus Jakarta Sans',sans-serif"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" class="flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg>Fingertips press keys — never fingernails</li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-xs sm:text-sm" style="color:#92400e;font-family:'Plus Jakarta Sans',sans-serif"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" class="flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg>Wrists stay level — neither bent up nor drooping down</li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-xs sm:text-sm" style="color:#92400e;font-family:'Plus Jakarta Sans',sans-serif"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" class="flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg>Right hand melody, left hand pumps bellows steadily</li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-xs sm:text-sm" style="color:#92400e;font-family:'Plus Jakarta Sans',sans-serif"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" class="flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg>Practice 20 min max before taking a break</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="prose-hm">
      <h2>Sitting Position Fundamentals</h2>
      <p>Good technique starts with how you sit. Cross-legged on the floor is traditional and comfortable for many Indian learners. If using a chair ensure the harmonium is on a table at elbow height — not too high forcing your shoulders up or too low bending your wrists down. Your shoulders should be relaxed never tense or raised.</p>

      <h2>Hand Position</h2>
      <p>Rest your right hand naturally over the keys with fingers gently curved — imagine holding a tennis ball very lightly. Your wrist should be level with the keyboard surface neither bent upward nor drooping downward. This neutral wrist position is critical for preventing repetitive strain injury during long practice sessions.</p>

      <h2>Fingering for the Scale</h2>
      <p>For the natural scale Sa Re Ga Ma Pa Dha Ni use fingers 1-2-3-1-2-3-4-5 (thumb equals 1, little finger equals 5). When thumb passes under finger 3 at the Ma-Pa transition do it smoothly without jerking the hand. This standard fingering pattern allows smooth scale playing across the full octave without awkward hand repositioning.</p>

      <h2>Left Hand Bellows Technique</h2>
      <p>Your left hand pumps the bellows rhythmically to maintain consistent air pressure. A very common beginner mistake is pumping irregularly which creates uneven sound volume. Practice pumping the bellows with a consistent steady beat — matching the pulse of whatever you are playing. Silent smooth bellows pumping is the mark of an experienced player.</p>

      <h2>Common Mistakes and Fixes</h2>
      <p>Pressing keys with fingernails reduces control and damages the key surface — use fingertips. Collapsing your wrist downward causes fatigue and limits speed — keep it level. Holding breath while concentrating creates tension — breathe naturally. Tensing your shoulder or elbow wastes energy — stay loose. Check these points every few minutes during practice.</p>

    </div>
    <div class="mt-8 mb-6">
      <h2 class="font-display font-bold text-xl sm:text-2xl mb-3" style="color:#1c1008">Practice Now</h2>
